# Patch 0013 — Tab memory management (ROADMAP Phase 2; PLATFORM_PLAN.md).
#
# Discards background tabs untouched for longer than
# `kavacha.tabs.unload-after-minutes` (default 30; 0 disables): the tab's
# browser is torn down to free memory while the tab stays in the strip, and
# Firefox restores it from flushed session state when next selected. This is
# the timer-driven counterpart to Firefox's TabUnloader, which only fires
# under OS memory pressure.
#
# KavachaTabMemory.sys.mjs is a process singleton (init from ZenStartup,
# idempotent) running one nsITimer that sweeps every browser window each
# minute. It reuses gBrowser.explicitUnloadTabs() — the same primitive Zen's
# space archiving uses — which flushes tab state before discarding, so form
# input and scroll position survive. Excludes the selected tab, pinned tabs,
# Zen essentials, the empty-tab placeholder, and tabs playing audio / in
# Picture-in-Picture / sharing screen or camera; skips private windows
# entirely (their tabs aren't session-persisted, so a discard would be
# unrecoverable). The default is also shipped in ui/defaults/kavacha-ux.js
# so it's documented and adjustable; the module's code default matches.
#
# Marionette-verified: sweep discards loaded background tabs (pending +
# discarded attributes), spares the selected tab, and skips already-pending
# ones. Applies on top of 0012.
